<h1>Examples</h1>

<section>
	<p class="example-intro">Faulty Parallelism occurs when elements in a sentence that are similar in terms of their meaning to the sentence but different in terms of their individual form or part of speech are treated as if they are the same. To correct faulty parallelism, match nouns with nouns, verbs with verbs, and other similarly constructed phrases with their respective matches. The following examples will cover different types of faulty parallelism. </p>
</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The nurse checked the patient's temperature, gave him his medicine, and a snack. <span class="red">FAULTY PARALLELISM!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">Here we see faulty parallelism occuring with a list of actions. The first two items in the list, "checked the patient's temperature" and "gave him his medicine", are actions, but the third, "a snack", is a noun. To correct the error, we need to change the form of the last item so that it matches the others.</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The nurse checked the patient's temperature, gave him his medicine, and served him a snack. <span class="green">CORRECT!</span></h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">The faulty parallelism in our example is corrected by converting the noun, "a snack", into the action, "served him a snack", which gives it a form that is parallel with the other items in the list.</p>
