</section>

<section>
	<h4 class="example example-sentence example-example">The nurse carried the sample, the chart, and opened the door, explaining the events to the rest of the team as she went. <span class="red">FAULTY PARALLELISM!</span></h4>
	<p class="example example-explanation example-explanation">This example's faulty parallelism comes from another mismatch of nouns and actions. This time the action, "opened the door", is included in the list of items the nurse carried. "Opening the door" should not be placed in a parallel relation with the objects in the list because it is in fact a parallel action to the parent action to which the objects belong, "The nurse carried".</p>
	<h4 class="example example-corrected example-corrected">The nurse carried the sample and the chart and opened the door, explaining the events to the rest of the team as she went. <span class="green">CORRECT!</span></h4>
	<p class="example corrected-explanation example-corrected-explanation">We fix the faulty parallelism in our example by separating our secondary action, "opened the door", from the list of the objects of our first action, "the nurse carried". This places the two actions in parallel structure, which aligns with the sentence's intended meaning.</p>
